ture is shown in Figure 2 . We refer readers to Peng et al. [ 13 ] for details of the base model. Figure 2 : Model architecture of VibeVoice-ASR-BitNet. Left: VAE tokenizer, 7-stage ConvNeXt with I8_S fused operators. Right: LM decoder, 28-layer Transformer with I2_S ternary weights. 2.2 Heterogeneous Quantization The two stages of VibeVoice-ASR exhibit fundamentally different computational profiles, motivating a heterogeneous quantization strategy rather than a uniform precision reduction. 2.2.1 I8_S: Full-Pipeline INT8 for VAE Tokenizer Memory Traffic Analysis. Each ConvNeXt block consists of a depthwise mixer convolution (implemented via im2col + matrix multiply) and a two-layer FFN ( D → 4 ​ D → D D\\to 4D\\to D ). For channel dimension D D , sequence length L L , and kernel size k = 8 k=8 , the per-block weight parameter count and activation data volume are: W \\displaystyle W = D ​ k ⏟ mixer + 8 ​ D 2 ⏟ FFN \\displaystyle=\\underbrace{Dk}_{\\text{mixer}}+\\underbrace{8D^{2}}_{\\text{FFN}} (1) A \\displaystyle A = 2 ​ D ​ k ​ L ⏟ im2col + 12 ​ D ​ L ⏟ FFN I/O \\displaystyle=\\underbrace{2DkL}_{\\text{im2col}}+\\underbrace{12DL}_{\\text{FFN I/O}} (2) Specifically, W W sums the depthwise convolution kernel ( D × k D\\times k parameters) and the two FFN matrices ( D × 4 ​ D + 4 ​ D × D = 8 ​ D 2 D\\times 4D+4D\\times D=8D^{2} ). A A sums the im2col read/write traffic ( D × k × L D\\times k\\times L elements read, plus D × k × L D\\times k\\times L elements written to the intermediate buffer) and all FFN activation I/O ( 4 ​ D ​ L 4DL per linear layer × \\times 3 passes: input, intermediate, output). Table 1 shows the per-stage breakdown for a 20 s audio input (480k samples at 24 kHz). Stage D D L L Depth Weights (M) Activations (M) Act / W 0 32 480,000 3 0.03 1,290 50,909 1 64 240,000 3 0.10 1,290 12,923 2 128 120,000 3 0.40 1,290 3,256 3 256 30,000 3 1.6 645 409 4 512 6,000 3 6.3 258 41 5 1,024 1,200 3 25.2 103 4 6 2,048 150 8 268.6 69 0.3 Total 302 4,946 16.4 Ta