ses, because the fixed overhead of pipeline initialization is amortized over longer inputs. Audio Duration 1 Thread 2 Threads 3 Threads 4 Threads 6 Threads 8 Threads 5 s 2.11 1.22 0.89 0.76 0.60 0.54 10 s 2.05 1.13 0.82 0.69 0.53 0.47 20 s 1.98 1.08 0.77 0.63 0.49 0.42 40 s 1.96 1.05 0.76 0.61 0.47 0.41 Table 3: End-to-end Real-Time Factor under different audio durations and thread counts. Bold indicates real-time, RTF < 1 <1 . To understand the source of speedup, we profile the VAE tokenizer and LM decoder separately. Figure 5 compares the VAE inference time under FP16 and I8_S quantization. The I8_S VAE achieves 1.3 × 1.3\\times – 2.0 × 2.0\\times speedup, with the gain increasing at higher thread counts due to better SIMD utilization under reduced data width. Figure 5 : VAE tokenizer inference time (s) vs. thread count (20 s audio). Numbers above I8_S bars indicate speedup over FP16. Figure 6 presents the LM decoder profiling results. I2_S achieves ∼ 2.5 × {\\sim}2.5\\times speedup on prefill and ∼ 4 × {\\sim}4\\times on decode. The higher decode speedup is expected: decode is purely weight-IO bound at batch size 1, where the 8 × 8\\times weight compression of I2_S relative to FP16 is most effective. FP16 decode scales poorly beyond 4 threads due to memory bandwidth saturation, while I2_S continues to benefit from additional threads. Figure 6 : LM decoder inference time (s) vs. thread count (20 s audio). (a) Prefill stage. (b) Decode stage. Numbers above I2_S bars indicate speedup over FP16. 3.3 Accuracy Table 4 compares WER and CER across 15 benchmarks. We include VibeVoice-ASR-7B as an upper-bound reference to quantify the accuracy gap introduced by model compression; however, since its 7B LM is 4.7 × 4.7\\times larger than the other models in this comparison, it does not participate in the ranking. Among models of comparable size, VibeVoice-ASR-BitNet achieves the lowest WER/CER on MLC-EN, AMI-ihm, AMI-sdm, and VoxPopuli. Despite the aggressive compression from 7B to 1.5B with ternary quantization, the accuracy degradation remains modest, typically 1–4% absolute WER increase on most benchmarks. Parakeet leads on read-speech English benchmarks due to its English-specialized design, while SenseVoice and FunASR dominate Chinese benchmarks with Chinese-focused training data. Notably, as an LM-based architecture, VibeVoice-ASR natively supports multilingual recognition across 6+ languages—a capability absen", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8a858c48eceffe6c", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# DLPO: Diffusion Model Loss-Guided Reinforcement Learning for Fine-Tuning Text-to-Speech Diffusion Models\narXiv: 2405.14632\nAuthors: Jingyi Chen, Ju-Seung Byun, Micha Elsner, Andrew Perrault\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We are the first to apply reinforcement learning to improve the speech quality of text-to-speech diffusion models.\n  2. We evaluate current RL methods for fine-tuning diffusion models in the text-to-speech setting.\n  3. We introduce diffusion loss-guided policy optimization which incorporates the original diffusion model loss as a penalty in the reward function to effectively prevent model deviation and fine-tune text-to-speech models.\n  4. We investigate the impact of diffusion gradients on fine-tuning text-to-speech diffusion models and the effect of different denoising steps, and conduct a human experiment to evaluate the speech quality of generated audio.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-NAR-Diffusion, TTS/功能-RL优化\n---PAPER1---\n# TASTE: Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding for Spoken Language Modeling\narXiv: 2504.07053\nAuthors: Liang-Hsuan Tseng, Yi-Chang Chen, Kuan-Yi Lee, Da-Shan Shiu, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding (TASTE), an end-to-end approach that aligns speech tokens with corresponding text transcriptions during the tokenization stage to bridge the modality gap.\n  2. Proposes a specialized cross-attention mechanism that uses text as queries and frozen ASR encoder representations as keys and values to dynamically aggregate speech into text-aligned tokens without explicit alignment.\n  3. Demonstrates that TASTE preserves essential paralinguistic information while dramatically reducing speech token sequence length and achieving high reconstruction quality at an extremely low bitrate.\n  4. Enables straightforward joint text-speech spoken language modeling via one-to-one text-speech token correspondence and Low-Rank Adaptation on pre-trained text LLMs.\n  5. Shows that the resulting spoken language model outperforms other pre-trained SLMs in speech continuation and likelihood-based tasks while preserving the text QA capabilities of its base LLM.\n  6. Presents the first end-to-end approach that utilizes a reconstruction objective to learn a joint tokenization and embedding tailored for text-speech spoken language modeling.\n\nTags: 压缩, LALM, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, LALM/音频标记-融合\n---PAPER2---\n# Step-Audio 2 Technical Report\narXiv: 2507.16632\nAuthors: Boyong Wu, Chao Yan, Chen Hu, Cheng Yi, Chengli Feng, Fei Tian, Feiyu Shen, Gang Yu, Haoyang Zhang, Jingbei Li, Mingrui Chen, Peng Liu, Wang You, Xiangyu Tony Zhang, Xingyuan Li, Xuerui Yang, Yayue Deng, Yechang Huang, Yuxin Li, Yuxin Zhang, Zhao You, Brian Li, Changyi Wan, Hanpeng Hu, Jiangjie Zhen, Siyu Chen, Song Yuan, Xuelin Zhang, Yimin Jiang, Yu Zhou, Yuxiang Yang, Bingxin Li, Buyun Ma, Changhe Song, Dongqing Pang, Guoqiang Hu, Haiyang Sun, Kang An, Na Wang, Shuli Gao, Wei Ji, Wen Li, Wen Sun, Xuan Wen, Yong Ren, Yuankai Ma, Yufan Lu, Bin Wang, Bo Li, Changxin Miao, Che Liu, Chen Xu, Dapeng Shi, Dingyuan Hu, Donghang Wu, Enle Liu, Guanzhe Huang, Gulin Yan, Han Zhang, Hao Nie, Haonan Jia, Hongyu Zhou, Jianjian Sun, Jiaoren Wu, Jie Wu, Jie Yang, Jin Yang, Junzhe Lin, Kaixiang Li, Lei Yang, Liying Shi, Li Zhou, Longlong Gu, Ming Li, Mingliang Li, Mingxiao Li, Nan Wu, Qi Han, Qinyuan Tan, Shaoliang Pang, Shengjie Fan, Siqi Liu, Tiancheng Cao, Wanying Lu, Wenqing He, Wuxun Xie, Xu Zhao, Xueqi Li, Yanbo Yu, Yang Yang, Yi Liu, Yifan Lu, Yilei Wang, Yuanhao Ding, Yuanwei Liang, Yuanwei Lu, Yuchu Luo, Yuhe Yin, Yumeng Zhan, Yuxiang Zhang, Zidong Yang, Zixin Zhang, Binxing Jiao, Daxin Jiang, Heung-Yeung Shum, Jiansheng Chen, Jing Li, Xiangyu Zhang, Yibo Zhu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Integrates discrete audio token generation into language modeling to achieve genuine end-to-end speech conversation and enhance responsiveness to paralinguistic information.\n  2. Leverages a latent audio encoder and reasoning-centric reinforcement learning to improve speech and audio understanding.\n  3. Incorporates retrieval-augmented generation and external tool calling, including a novel audio search tool for timbre and speaking style switching, to mitigate hallucination and leverage real-world knowledge.\n  4. Develops a multi-stage training strategy trained on millions of hours of diverse audio and textual data to ensure robust intelligence and expressiveness.\n  5. Introduces new evaluation benchmarks for paralinguistic understanding and tool calling to assess complex audio interaction capabilities.\n  6. Achieves state-of-the-art performance across multiple audio understanding and speech conversation benchmarks, outperforming existing open-source and commercial solutions.\n\nTags: LALM/音频标记-融合, LALM/对话型-交错标记, LALM/后训练-GRPO, LALM/训练-指令微调\n---PAPER3---", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fe9c1bc6-5ae7-48ce-99f1-21f722918975", "uuid": "3c88ef6d-6744-4e3c-b0aa-34ef9fe5b2e2", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T06:20:41.806Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# DLPO: Diffusion Model Loss-Guided Reinforcement Learning for Fine-Tuning Text-to-Speech Diffusion Models\narXiv: 2405.14632\nAuthors: Jingyi Chen, Ju-Seung Byun, Micha Elsner, Andrew Perrault\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We are the first to apply reinforcement learning to improve the speech quality of text-to-speech diffusion models.\n  2. We evaluate current RL methods for fine-tuning diffusion models in the text-to-speech setting.\n  3. We introduce diffusion loss-guided policy optimization which incorporates the original diffusion model loss as a penalty in the reward function to effectively prevent model deviation and fine-tune text-to-speech models.\n  4. We investigate the impact of diffusion gradients on fine-tuning text-to-speech diffusion models and the effect of different denoising steps, and conduct a human experiment to evaluate the speech quality of generated audio.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-NAR-Diffusion, TTS/功能-RL优化\n---PAPER1---\n# TASTE: Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding for Spoken Language Modeling\narXiv: 2504.07053\nAuthors: Liang-Hsuan Tseng, Yi-Chang Chen, Kuan-Yi Lee, Da-Shan Shiu, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding (TASTE), an end-to-end approach that aligns speech tokens with corresponding text transcriptions during the tokenization stage to bridge the modality gap.\n  2. Proposes a specialized cross-attention mechanism that uses text as queries and frozen ASR encoder representations as keys and values to dynamically aggregate speech into text-aligned tokens without explicit alignment.\n  3. Demonstrates that TASTE preserves essential paralinguistic information while dramatically reducing speech token sequence length and achieving high reconstruction quality at an extremely low bitrate.\n  4. Enables straightforward joint text-speech spoken language modeling via one-to-one text-speech token correspondence and Low-Rank Adaptation on pre-trained text LLMs.\n  5. Shows that the resulting spoken language model outperforms other pre-trained SLMs in speech continuation and likelihood-based tasks while preserving the text QA capabilities of its base LLM.\n  6. Presents the first end-to-end approach that utilizes a reconstruction objective to learn a joint tokenization and embedding tailored for text-speech spoken language modeling.\n\nTags: 压缩, LALM, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, LALM/音频标记-融合\n---PAPER2---\n# Step-Audio 2 Technical Report\narXiv: 2507.16632\nAuthors: Boyong Wu, Chao Yan, Chen Hu, Cheng Yi, Chengli Feng, Fei Tian, Feiyu Shen, Gang Yu, Haoyang Zhang, Jingbei Li, Mingrui Chen, Peng Liu, Wang You, Xiangyu Tony Zhang, Xingyuan Li, Xuerui Yang, Yayue Deng, Yechang Huang, Yuxin Li, Yuxin Zhang, Zhao You, Brian Li, Changyi Wan, Hanpeng Hu, Jiangjie Zhen, Siyu Chen, Song Yuan, Xuelin Zhang, Yimin Jiang, Yu Zhou, Yuxiang Yang, Bingxin Li, Buyun Ma, Changhe Song, Dongqing Pang, Guoqiang Hu, Haiyang Sun, Kang An, Na Wang, Shuli Gao, Wei Ji, Wen Li, Wen Sun, Xuan Wen, Yong Ren, Yuankai Ma, Yufan Lu, Bin Wang, Bo Li, Changxin Miao, Che Liu, Chen Xu, Dapeng Shi, Dingyuan Hu, Donghang Wu, Enle Liu, Guanzhe Huang, Gulin Yan, Han Zhang, Hao Nie, Haonan Jia, Hongyu Zhou, Jianjian Sun, Jiaoren Wu, Jie Wu, Jie Yang, Jin Yang, Junzhe Lin, Kaixiang Li, Lei Yang, Liying Shi, Li Zhou, Longlong Gu, Ming Li, Mingliang Li, Mingxiao Li, Nan Wu, Qi Han, Qinyuan Tan, Shaoliang Pang, Shengjie Fan, Siqi Liu, Tiancheng Cao, Wanying Lu, Wenqing He, Wuxun Xie, Xu Zhao, Xueqi Li, Yanbo Yu, Yang Yang, Yi Liu, Yifan Lu, Yilei Wang, Yuanhao Ding, Yuanwei Liang, Yuanwei Lu, Yuchu Luo, Yuhe Yin, Yumeng Zhan, Yuxiang Zhang, Zidong Yang, Zixin Zhang, Binxing Jiao, Daxin Jiang, Heung-Yeung Shum, Jiansheng Chen, Jing Li, Xiangyu Zhang, Yibo Zhu\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: audio_understanding\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Integrates discrete audio token generation into language modeling to achieve genuine end-to-end speech conversation and enhance responsiveness to paralinguistic information.\n  2. Leverages a latent audio encoder and reasoning-centric reinforcement learning to improve speech and audio understanding.\n  3. Incorporates retrieval-augmented generation and external tool calling, including a novel audio search tool for timbre and speaking style switching, to mitigate hallucination and leverage real-world knowledge.\n  4. Develops a multi-stage training strategy trained on millions of hours of diverse audio and textual data to ensure robust intelligence and expressiveness.\n  5. Introduces new evaluation benchmarks for paralinguistic understanding and tool calling to assess complex audio interaction capabilities.\n  6. Achieves state-of-the-art performance across multiple audio understanding and speech conversation benchmarks, outperforming existing open-source and commercial solutions.\n\nTags: LALM/音频标记-融合, LALM/对话型-交错标记, LALM/后训练-GRPO, LALM/训练-指令微调\n---PAPER3---", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
